An argument, second only in weight to this, is founded upon the Odes (2. ro and 3. 19) which have reference to Licinius Murena, the brother of Terentia, Maecenas' wife (see also on Od 2. a. 5). Murena was executed for participation with Fannius Caepio in a conspiracy against Augustus in tac. aa. The presumption seems very strong that even if Horace’s feelings would have allowed him to publish these poems, and especially Od. a. 10, after his friend’s catastrophe, he would have been deterred by the knowledge that the reminiscences must be displeasing to Maecenas as well as to Augustus. The arguments for postponing the publication of the Odes to a later date are not such as can really be set against these con· sideratious. They turn mainly on Od. 1. 3, which is taken to refer to the voyage of Virgil to Athens in the last year of his life, tac. 19: and on the supposed allusious (the strongest case is Od. a. 9) to the expedition of Tiberius into Armenia, and the restoration of the standards by the Parthians in uc. ao. Some remarks on these points will be found in the Introductions to Od. 1. 3 aud a. 9. There re- mains the possibility that these (and if these, then other) Odes may have been inserted after the first publication. It will be seen that this is not likely to have been the case with 1. 3; and the theory of any such insertione is perhaps hardly compatible with that pause in lyric composition between the publication of Books i-iii aud the com· mencement of Book iv, which is implied in Suetonius' statement, and in Horace's own words, Od. 4. 1. r, Epp. 1. 1. 1-10.
